tured and then escaped to the United States, where he was imprisoned in Queens, and then undertook a hunger strike in protest. To provide a framework for understanding stories like these, Dow gives a brief history of immigration laws and practices in the United States—including the repercussions of September 11 and present-day policies. His book reveals that current immigration detentions are best understood not as a well-intentioned response to terrorism but rather as part of the larger context of INS secrecy and excessive authority. American Gulag exposes the full story of a cruel prison system that is operating today with an astonishing lack of accountability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAlien detention centersxUnited States. 0aAlien detention centerszUnited States. 0aEmigration and immigration lawxUnited States. 0aEmigration and immigration lawzUnited States. 0aHuman rightsxUnited States. 0aHuman rightszUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyxUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aamerica.  aamerican gulag.  aamerican prisons.  adetention centers.  afederal officials.  ahuman cruelty.  ahuman rights violations.  ahuman rights.  aimmigration and nationalization service.  aimmigration detention.  aimmigration history.  aimmigration laws.  aimmigration policies.  aimmigration prisons.  ainhumane conditions.  ains facilities.  ains prisoners.  ains.  ainvestigative journalism.  ajailers.  aprison system.  aprisoners.  aracial profiling.  aracism.  arepression.  aseptember 11.  aus immigration policies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/97805